A simple calculation of your heart disease risk

JacquesFGD
9/21/2014

Prevalence of heart disease

It is the leading cause of death in the United States (and many other Western countries).

As this map shows, some populations are more at risk than others.

We want to provide an easy way to calculate an aggregated risk.

Many potential risk factors...

Some factors are not modifiable

  • Age
  • History of heart disease in the family (i.e. genetic)

But most factors are influenced by lifestyle

  • Cholesterol levels
  • Smoking
  • High blood pressure
  • Lack of physical exercise

Here we will focus on the 4 parameters in bold

The core of the app

The app uses these 4 parameters to calculate an aggregated risk according to the following formula (which is meant to be just a example!)

riskCalc <- function(age,history,chol,sys) {
  risk <- 1
  if (age > 55) {risk <- risk * 2^((age-55)/10)}
  if (history) {risk <- risk*5}
  if (chol>200) {risk <- risk * (1+(chol-200)/10)}
  if (sys>120) {risk <- risk * 2^((sys-120)/20)}
  return(risk)}
